35	Denver Urban Gardens	Denver Urban Gardens (DUG) hosts a large network community gardens and food forests across metro Denver. Grown out of a grassroots movement that began in North Denver in the 80's, DUG is now one of the country's largest urban agriculture networks.\n\nDUG provides affordable garden plots, volunteer garden leaders, seeds and seedlings, soil testing, and community support to thousands of active gardeners who collectively speak 18+ languages. Many participants are low-income households or residents in food deserts. Gardeners donate 10% of their harvest each season for community food redistribution.	https://dug.org	https://res.cloudinary.com/dr3gnrygp/image/upload/v1773674165/hseuq26nwzmgxrvghrxw.png	{environment,hunger,education}	\N	74-2374848	2026-03-16 22:25:20.316094	2026-03-18 15:43:32.444389	denver-urban-gardens	1985	https://dug.org/get-involved/volunteer/	f	t	1031 33rd Street, Suite 100, Denver, CO 80205	https://dug.org/give/	t	- 200+ community gardens and food forests across Denver\n- 2,875 community gardeners\n- 627,926 pounds of food grown annually\n- 62,500+ pounds of food distributed\n- 40,000+ Denverites with access to fresh, locally grown produce	Denver Urban Gardens hosts gardens embedded in neighborhoods across Denver metro. Below are a number of public community gardens, but visit dug.org to see the the updated list of available plots and join a garden near you.	https://res.cloudinary.com/dr3gnrygp/image/upload/v1773694367/iw0zl4jfmxugrvjlnlgw.jpg	https://res.cloudinary.com/dr3gnrygp/image/upload/v1773698563/vxvrmu5bikje7j8yxgex.webp	https://res.cloudinary.com/dr3gnrygp/image/upload/v1773698566/qkmzoaqce1qzvqfcd7j9.jpg	(home)**Community Gardens**A network of neighborhood gardens providing affordable plots, volunteer Garden Leaders, seeds, soil testing, and support for thousands of active gardeners across metro Denver.\n(tree)**Food Forests**Dozens of lush, layered public spaces with perennial fruits, nuts, herbs, and pollinator plants free for the community to enjoy, with 614 fruit and nut trees tended by volunteer Tree Keepers.\n(education)**School Gardens**60+ school-based gardens connecting Denver students to hands-on food growing, environmental stewardship, and healthy food access.\n(people)**Community Programs**Workshops, volunteer workdays, free seeds and seedlings, composting programs, and community events for gardeners of all backgrounds.	Info and photography courtesy of Denver Urban Gardens.	Join a Garden	https://dug.org/gardens-food-forests/community-gardens/join-a-garden/	f	\N
